\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Yes. I was at Frensham Heights in England. By the way, higher maths. I\rquote ve never been that good, and now I\rquote 
m hopeless! But, I mean, even in those days, in my big career days, I had real limitations in theoretical mathematics. And the thing to stress about my statistics is that when I taught statistics 
at LSE, having done a degree and got a First and everything - to do with statistics - and the maths necessary for statistics up to degree level was no problem for me. I did all that very well. And then when I started teaching \endash 
 assistant lecturer, lecturer, reader, professor \endash 
 I was teaching numbers really, and above all, survey methodology, which became my specialty. In my Department, of which I became Head in the end, at LSE, there were some professors who were brilliant, like me, at numbers. There were o
ther statisticians - professors, readers - who actually were good at mathematics as such, so they would develop new theories of statistics. After all, statistics has always been a divided subject, as you, I\rquote m sure, know. There\rquote 
s theoretical statistics and there\rquote s applied statistics, and I\rquote 
ve always, shamelessly, been on the applied side, and became known for what I did on measuring the world. So apart from developing survey methods in which I did, I suppose, develop some new ways of sampling. Sampling theor
y I could manage, of course, but otherwise my excitement was to measure the world. So I wrote one book called, British Towns, I wrote with others, and suddenly the government asked me to go to Jamaica, I don\rquote t know why, to do a study of Jamaica
\rquote s standards
 of living. So I knew how to do that, I knew how to measure educational change, criminal change, etc. etc.. And then I I suddenly got an invitation from God knows whom to do a report on the state of the dental profession in England, so I wrote a little bo
oklet. And I knew how to measure. I knew how to decide what mattered in terms of the success of the dental profession, in which I had no interest whatever! And so I started doing research into the numbers. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 When you mentioned the more theoretical people, one of those that you\rquote 
ve, I think, referred to, is Maurice Kelsall? Is that right? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Kendall. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Kendall, Kendall - can you explain about his ideas? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Well, you see, the point is that statistics has always been - I mean, one\rquote 
s simply got to accept that statistics is a subject - that that name is used whether one is describing people like me, who know how to measure almost anything in the world - these are the applied statisticians. And then there are the theoretical statistic
ians, who have no interest in the real world. I mean, they\rquote re mathematicians really. And so taking the great people of my time \endash  David Cox, still alive, who\rquote 
s got every honour in the world, and for developing theoretical statistics. Now, he\rquote s a nice man, and he doesn\rquote t look down on applied statisticians like me. I mean, we\rquote ve always respected each other. But there are some people \endash 
 Finney, David Finney \endash  who really regards me - he\rquote s very nice to me, and we\rquote re friends, but, I mean, he regards me as sort of irrelevant to his subject really. And then the really great people, like R.A. Fisher \endash 
 Sir Ronald Fisher \endash  who developed statistical theory, and with whom one would argue about different aspects of statistical theory. R.A. Fisher, Frank Yates, there are quite a few truly great men \endash  and some women \endash 
 who have absolutely no interest, they would certainly not pick up a book by me, called British Towns, they probably wouldn\rquote t even pick up a book which tells [about] survey methods, which is the best book I\rquote ve done
, which was partly theoretical, but theory of surveys, not of statistics as such. It is a split subject, and some universities \endash  I don\rquote t know about Essex \endash  some universities, what they would call the \'93Statistics Department\'94
, would not have people like me. I\rquote d be probably in - could be Economics, could be Sociology, Social Science. They wouldn\rquote 
t have me. Some departments, some universities - in some, which I think is better, like LSE, they are joined, because, ideally, people like me, who are applied statist
icians, ought to try to keep up with the theoretical side, which, obviously, I had to deal with in exams, and teach, up to a point. And I did try, but I was never clever enough, in mathematical terms, really to make an impact there. And conversely, I resp
ect the mathematical statisticians, like Sir Roy Allen, who was the Head of [LSE\rquote 
s] Department for some years, who is also a great economist, so he did bridge the world. But if I had to widen myself, it was in the direction not so much of economics, as sociology and social science and social administration, and most of what I\rquote 
ve written - well, a lot of what I\rquote ve written is on survey methods. Anyway, as I think told Jennifer [Wingate] when I was talking about my academic life, there was one terrible moment - actually you\rquote ve just referred to the person \endash 
 when a new professor came. I was only a reader then, and I was fine. And the Head of the Department was Sir Roy Allen, a famous economic statistician, and all his books straddle economics and statistics, and L
SE decided that we deserved a second professor, who was more theoretical, because it was felt that, if anything, the Department was too applied. And they were lucky to get the best man in the country, one of the best in the world, Sir Maurice Kendall 
\endash  and all his books are upstairs (well, so are Roy Allen\rquote s). Funnily enough, his day job, he was Chairman of the Chamber of Shipping \endash  don\rquote t ask me why \endash 
 but he was just an exceptional person, and spent any free moment, writing books about theoretical statistics \endash  they remain the great books. He didn\rquote t so much invent new theories, like some people, like Jim Durbin did, he didn\rquote 
t. But he had a way of summarising their whole - I mean, upstairs are two vast volumes \endash  this big \endash  by Maurice Kendall, called The Advanced Theory of Statistics. He was a terrifying person, and he became our professor. And our first meeting 
\endash  and I think I did tell Jennifer about this \endash  our first meeting of the whole Department, clearly he was more powerful than Roy Allen, and he said he had decided who should teach which courses next academic year. \'93Moser, you\rquote 
re going to teach ... Variance and Covariance\'94 And I said, \'93I\rquote m sorry, Professor, I don\rquote t know enough about it\'94. \'93I\rquote m sorry. You\rquote re teaching that next year.\'94 And for two years I had a
 terrifying and restless life, because I didn\rquote t understand - it wasn\rquote t just that I couldn\rquote t teach it, I didn\rquote t understand it \endash  covariance and variance analysis. It\rquote s one of the more advanced \'85
 But Maurice knew what he was doing, he realised I was weak on that side of things, and that wouldn\rquote 
t do, and his order was his order. And so, literally, literally, every week, I was one week ahead of the students. I struggled and struggled and struggled to understand the analysis of variance and covariance. I went int
o the lecture room to face these 30 or 40 students, went straight to the board, and when the 60 minutes were up, I said, \'93I\rquote m sorry, I\rquote ve got to rush now\'94
, because I was terrified there were questions, because everything I needed for that lecture, I\rquote d prepared, and it would last the hour - well, it wasn\rquote 
t quite an hour, I think it was 50 minutes. And I always got away with it, because I always learnt enough by myself. But it was terrifying, and is not the way one should be teaching, but, there we are! I told him \endash 
 in due course we became very very close friends, used to travel together - a sweet man really \endash  but I told him that he sort of destroyed my happiness, really, for those years, because I was too frightened on the next lecture that I had to give. An
d my only total protection was to avoid questions. Any question would have gone beyond. Anyway, that was the worst part of my career. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Could we perhaps go back to when you were an undergraduate, and I was wondering whether there were any inspiring teachers at LSE. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Well, they were, but they weren\rquote t so much on the statistics side. When I was a student \endash  that was \rquote 40-\rquote 
43, and then I went into the War \endash  and if I now answer straight the question \endash  were there inspiring teachers? The answer is yes, 
but not in statistics. In statistics, there were some very good - Roy Allen was around part of that time, there were two or three others, a chap called Rose, a chap called Brown, they\rquote 
re all good memories, and they were all quite good teachers, but nobody who would raise me to a great new level \endash  not in statistics, they were all away in the War. Well, it wasn\rquote 
t that great a Department, actually, then. It became great later. It did become great later, and I obviously had a part in it, because it did find a w
ay of linking applied and theoretical statistics, which, really, every university should do. Warwick now does it rather well. I don\rquote t know about Essex. Anyway, but there were inspiring teachers. We were evacuated to Cambridge \endash 
 LSE was in Cambridge \endash  and above all, we had Laski, and he was \'85
 he became a great friend and supporter of mine, so to speak, later. So there was Laski. Occasionally there was Robbins, who became my closest friend in life. [TELEPHONE INTERRUPTION] There were some wonderful - I mean, 
when I think back to being a student at LSE during those three years, they made my life because I could listen to Laski, I could listen to Tawney \endash 
 the greatest historian of all time. And a few others, and occasionally Robbins, and all the time Hayek \endash  economist \endash 
 so, I mean, these people who escaped the War for some reason. I suppose Tawney was too old, Hayek was probably still Austrian. And I did meet Keynes, but Keynes didn\rquote t teach me. Keynes wasn\rquote 
t teaching at LSE, but I did meet him. So it was a great time. But anyway, I did well in statistics, and I was clear that this was my subject, because I so enjoyed numbers! But the difference between \endash 
 and all your colleagues at Essex would share this view \endash  the difference between two statisticians, one of whom loves numbers (that\rquote s me!) and one who couldn\rquote t care about numbers, but loves algebra, that\rquote 
s not me! And one is the theoretical side, which is very important, but it is a sort of different subject. So I had - going back to your question about LSE as a stu
dent - wonderful time - but mainly because we were a small university, a small college evacuated there. We had all these wonderful academics. I mean, to have gone to college and to \endash  I\rquote 
ve only mentioned the two giants, Tawney - well, Hayek is a giant, yeah, so he\rquote s a giant in history. Tawney. But nobody on the statistics side, I think. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Now, once you\rquote d come back to LSE, you\rquote 
ve already mentioned this book on Jamaica, I was wondering how you set about doing that. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Well, it\rquote s a good question, be
cause God knows how I did it! I mean, how did I write a book about Jamaica, and in almost the same year, a book about dentistry? But they were rather marginal to my life. In a way, it\rquote s painfully simple, because if you\rquote 
re sent, as I was, by the government - I must have been known already, up to a point, because the Colonial Office wanted to assess how Jamaica was doing as a country. I must have had a bit of a reputation for measuring quality of life really \endash  that
\rquote s what it\rquote s about. Now they all talk about \'93happiness\'94, well, I\rquote 
m not in that particular game. First of all, you spend a lot of time just sitting on your bum and working out what matters to Jamaica. Is crime increasingly under control? It was a very criminal country in those days. Is education improving at last? What
\rquote s happening to the birth rate? So you probably think of 20 or maybe 30 \endash  this is just sitting on your bum \endash 
 20 or 30 things that matter. You then, before you you look for a single number, but you know that those are the 20 or 30 things that you really want to be able to put in your report \endash 
 how they were 20 years ago, 50 years ago, 100 years ago, last year \endash  prospects. And then much more interesting, how do they relate to one another? Obviously there\rquote s a relation between education and crime, that\rquote 
s got to be brought out in this. This is before I\rquote ve set foot in Jamaica. So it\rquote s not very difficult, anybody could do this, but that\rquote s what I learnt to be good at \endash  how to measure life, things that matter. And I\rquote 
ll tell you, in a minute, how that ended up. But sticking to Jamaica, then I went to Jamaica, and I had three months. I had a very good time there, nice people \endash  but that doesn\rquote 
t come into this interview! I was living at the University in Kingston, and I made my contacts with all the Government Departments, and gradually \endash  I\rquote ve got it somewhere, but it would take some finding \endash 
 I wrote what turned out to be rather a useful oversight on what is happening to the nation, to that country, how it has developed. Ultimately, obviously, it depends 
on how good the statistics are. So obviously I made my contact with the Statistics Office. So, in a way, it\rquote 
s very simple-minded. But the skill is how to try to link different aspects of quality of life together, and how to assess good figures from lousy figures, and the only pride I have in what I\rquote 
ve done as a statistician, in many different situations, I did get very good at assessing the quality of figures, and improving them, of course, for this country. I mean if you know a publication called Social Trends \endash  that was my invention 
\endash  and that really showed the way I thought. And when I feel over-modest about it, I realise that it\rquote s not equal to the brilliance of the theoretical statisticians; when I don\rquote t feel that modest about it, I realise that it actua
lly does more good for the world. And I\rquote ve always been more interested in improving life, and doing this kind of thing does improve life. And funnily enough \endash  I don\rquote t know whether we ever got this far, we probably did \endash 
 at the very end of my statistical career, very near the end, there was a very great man in my life \endash  amongst all the other great men \endash 
 he was called Richard Stone, Sir Richard Stone. He was one of the inventors of measuring National Product in the eighties, 1980s. The real originator of measuring GNP which, after all, one can\rquote 
t exaggerate the importance of it every day, was an American called Kusnetz, but at almost the same time Keynes was the English inventor of measuring National Income. And so Keynes and Kusnetz - now, Keynes\rquote s assistant a
t that time was this young man who later became Sir Richard Stone, and he really developed [the measure], and not only did he develop it from its beginnings \endash 
 and, by the way, I have, upstairs somewhere, the first White Paper measuring National Product, which is four pages - four pages, now it takes 500 pages to explain all the figures. At that time there were only enough figures for four pages. And I\rquote 
m really part of that development, but much later. So this is the most incredible applied statistical invention of all time, otherwise we\rquote d know even less of what\rquote 
s going on. And as I say, Keynes and Kusnetz. But then came this young man called Dick Stone, and Dick Stone not only developed it beyond recognition, but also helped every single - he went to the United Nations \endash 
 he helped every single country in the world to learn how to measure their National Income. Unbelievable! For which he got a Nobel Prize, by the way. He also partly got the Nobel Prize \endash  and this is where I come into the picture \endash 
 we became great friends, and we worked together, and he said to me one day, \'93We\rquote ve got to go beyond measuring National Income\'94. He wasn\rquote t thinking of happiness, he was too clever for that. He said, \'93What we\rquote 
ve got to find a way of showing how, in the country ... education, crime, health, all these things are developing, but not separately, everything is related in life\'94
, he said. So we sat at an enormous table with M.K. statistical tables, boxes, education across the top, crime across the side, etc., etc., etc., and we got quite a long way, and then he died. His wife tried to carry it on. And I\rquote 
ve tried, since then - it\rquote s still not been done. But Dick really got the Nobel Prize partly for this idea of linking together \endash  and that\rquote s something I\rquote ve done all my life really, or tried to do \endash 
 linking together all the different aspects of quality of life. Unfortunately, our great Prime Minister, Mr. Cameron, got hold of the idea that it would be nice not just to have to measure National Income, because it\rquote s bad news, but he jum
ped straight to \'93happiness\'94, which is balls, because it\rquote s unmeasurable anyway. But it\rquote s quite interesting. So we\rquote re sort of back in the game, now I\rquote m slightly back in the game. So I mention that now because, even now, I
\rquote m getting back slightly into that aspect of applied statistics, trying to learn how to measure. There\rquote s a human being downstairs, so that must mean coffee! I know I\rquote m taking much too long, but I know Jennifer knows I\rquote 
m like that, and I can\rquote t stop! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
