\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 No. I had written one book on survey methods, which was a success, so I got rather big for my boots, and I thought, \'93
Well, I can write books!\'94 And there was a book \endash  it\rquote s a terrible story, I probably wasn\rquote t honest enough to tell you! There was a book by a man ca
lled Sir Alexander Carr-Saunders, who also happened to be Director of LSE when I was there, and he, with a Welshman call Caradog Jones, wrote a book called, Social Conditions in England and Wales \endash  that\rquote s not exactly right \endash 
 which was a standard book, but 
quite out of date. I was very self-confident in those days, and believe it or not, I spent six months, or nine months, bringing it up to date without telling them! How could I have done? So I produced a new edition of their book! And really it\rquote 
s a very goo
d, it became a very good book. It was quite a good book before, and I always thought, because it was my interest, you know, how to characterise England and Wales in statistical terms, with text. And it was good, but it was out of date, and not really quit
e professional enough, so I improved it. I spent, oh, the best part of a year. And one day I had a call from my Director, \'85 and he was a sweet man, but I\rquote ll never forget the moment he said, \'93I gather you\rquote ve improved my book\'94
. Anyway, I just apologised, and apologised, and apologised. And just - I said, \'93I\rquote ll come and apologise\'94. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
