\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 I\rquote ve lost count! And it is in several languages. And I know exactly why it\rquote 
s been such a success, because it avoids the more theoretical \endash  this gets back to the basic point \endash  it\rquote s written in a language so simple, but technical
ly absolutely correct. I mean, it is very correct on sampling methodology and so on, so of course it covers all the technical side, but anybody can understand it. As you would know from Essex, there are thousands of people who love to do sociology, or soc
ial science, or economics, who are not good at statistics, but you have to do it as part of that, and you have to know about surveys, and here\rquote s a book that makes it so simple. That\rquote s because \endash  this is not modesty \endash  I\rquote 
ve got a fairly simple way of explaining things, and that\rquote s why, incidentally \endash  I might as well say it, I\rquote ve certainly said it to Jennifer \endash 
 I was a great success as an academic, as a teacher. As a researcher, not really, not really. None of my books produce new ideas, they produce new ways of 
putting things. I was a prime example of the sort of professor who universities bloody well should have, who loves teaching. I loved lecturing, I loved teaching, except analysis of covariance! I loved teaching, but I wasn\rquote 
t a great researcher, and there\rquote s room in universities for people, every bit. Every bit. If I hadn\rquote t gone sideways into the outside world \endash  the non-academic world \endash 
 for quite a while, which was a series of accidents, I would have gone on being a university professor, happily teaching for y
ears and years. I might have become a Vice-Chancellor, and I might have gone straight down that line, but, in fact, I went to do other things. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 

