\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Of course, I didn\rquote 
t invent random sampling. Random sampling is what the theoretical statisticians would always have gone to anyway, be
cause random is the centre of statistics. But in my book, in my survey book, and in my work generally, I pushed random sampling to the front of the survey world and made quota sampling to be avoided. Quota sampling, where you can get away with all kinds o
f biased samples, is still used by opinion pollsters, so I didn\rquote t invent a new method, but I developed good practical ways, affordable ways, in which randomness could be brought into the survey world, the social survey world, that\rquote s all. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 You were sa
ying that it was almost accidental that you left academic life. I was wondering whether you could explain how that happened. I mean, does it start with the Robbins Committee? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 I had the Chair at LSE. I joined Lionel Robbins in 1961, and there\rquote s abs
olutely no question that I went to great length in talking it over, that writing the Robbins Report \endash  because I was really the co-author with Lionel Robbins. That\rquote 
s unfair, in a way, because he ended up writing every word, anyway, I was his main colleague. I mean, by a vast distance the most interesting and important thing I\rquote 
ve ever done in my life, or ever will do, was to [work for this] wonderful Report. Six volumes sitting out there - well, one volume and the Report, and six volumes of appendices, which 
I wrote - those were the statistical appendices. So the first Report of that kind that was statistically beyond criticism. It really was. And that was me and Richard Layard \endash  Lord Layard \endash 
 and we had the staff. And Lionel Robbins was, I suppose, the greatest man I\rquote ve ever spent so much time with, and became a dear friend \endash 
 a great man. Lionel opened the first meeting of that Committee, of the Robbins Committee, historic Committee, in 1961. His first sentence was, \'93Nothing we\rquote re going to recommend - \'94 no, he put it positively, \'93Everything we\rquote 
re going to recommend has to have a sound statistical basis, that\rquote s why Claus Moser is here\'94. I mean, it was a desperate responsibility, but he meant it. He was a social scientist, an economist to his fingertips, of course \endash 
 a great man in that field. And he was just determined, and it\rquote s his way of talking back to that, because it was totally my making, as a statistician really, because although I\rquote 
d written my books before then, it was the first time that I had this public
 responsibility. I mean, he made it so public. And one has to remember that the reason that Committee was set up in 1961, by the Tory government, was because they felt the public criticism of the fact that only five per cent of children got to university 
\endash  five per cent. It\rquote s now 50 per cent. Five per cent. So shouldn\rquote 
t it be more? That was the question. And it was for me to answer. So it was a fantastic responsibility. There were people on the Committee who, in the first sort of general discussion, which I\rquote ll never forget, said, \'93No, five per cent is enough
\'94. Helen Gardner, the famous English professor, she said, \'93That\rquote s quite enough. Quite enough. No need\'94. So the Committee was divided from the first meeting. There were about three - she\rquote s the one who sticks to mind \endash 
 who felt that it should be very exclusive, and remain so. Lionel Robbins was determined that we should recommend an increase, and after two years\rquote  work, and seven volumes of statistics \endash  not all on this point \endash 
 but on this point the first volu
me of statistical research was the most original, which Richard Layard and I did together, was how to study the potential within a society, which is a difficult task and quite original. And that led the Committee ultimately - after two years sitting - to 
be very very daring, that we could go up to 15 per cent in ten years time, and that recommendation was accepted by the government. As I say, we\rquote re now at 50 per cent. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
