\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 No. In Germany, of course, I did maths, but it wasn\rquote 
t special. And being in Germany, all the teachers were tough, disciplined, and pretty good, so one didn\rquote t expect to be friendly with them. So I don\rquote t actual
ly - no, I do remember the maths teacher, but he was nothing special. But in Frensham Heights, he was special in the sense that he was the most straightforward educational teacher. All the others were more the modern school, you know, thinking of one
\rquote s nature and character as well as subject. No, nothing in Berlin. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 What was the name of the teacher in Frensham Heights? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 He was called Mr. Weedon, and he was Deputy Headmaster. He was rather necessary, in a way, necessary, I think, from the poin
t of view of the School as a whole, because nearly all the teachers were so friendly and warm and personable and all that, so it was quite easy not to learn a lot in subject terms. That\rquote 
s probably why our wonderful Headmaster chose him as his Deputy, because he was more straightforward, a good teacher, and he did get me very enthusiastic on maths, which I was ready to be anyway. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Yes. Why did your parents send you to Frensham Heights, do you think? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Well, that will always be a bit of a mystery in one sense. I mean, in one sense it wasn\rquote t a mystery because a cousin of mine 
\endash  I had five cousins \endash  and one of them, for reasons I simply have no idea, and I never did know, he was sent to Frensham Heights when he and his brother emigrated before us, 
and for some reason, his parents - my uncle and aunt - sent him to Frensham and I have no idea why. But he was very happy there. And so that\rquote 
s part of the background. But the more interesting background is that my parents obviously had enough insight into their two boys \endash  as they should have, but not necessarily do have \endash 
 and they realised that I was very arts-minded, especially music. I started playing the piano when I was five. Very arts-minded, and very slightly wild, slightly unusual, not a particularly
 straightforward pupil. So that led them to choose - they went to the educational, they came to London to interview the agency.... \'93Gabbatus and Three\'94. And they said, \'93That\rquote s a very nice school, very friendly, and not too disciplined\'94
 and so on, and that made them choose Frensham for me. My brother, my older brother, was much more straightforward throughout his life \endash  we were very close throughout his life - and clearly was a learner, and they sent him to Dulwich. Couldn
\rquote t be more different! A rather minor
 public school. Well, not that minor, but sort of. And the unfortunate result was that whereas I had a very happy four years, my brother had a rather unhappy time at Dulwich, partly because of anti-Semitism, which evidently was quite rife there \endash 
 teasing him for being Jewish and all that. And funnily enough, he later on converted to Christianity \endash  that\rquote 
s the one thing on which we were rather different. So they chose these two schools which, in a sense, fitted us, but my brother had the short straw. I think [Dulwich] probably was a good school, in its terms. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 It has a reputation, anyway. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Yes. I think so. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 And were there other Jewish children at Frensham Heights, then? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
