\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Well, what we did for the Robbins Report, and it occupied a whole volume \endash  Volume 1 of the appendices \endash  which we call 
\'93The Pool of Ability\'94, and which had to de
al with that question, because obviously, I mean, your question is absolutely right, because the reason for the Robbins Report was that only five per cent went to university, and after all that research the Committee was persuaded to recommend going up to
 15 per cent in ten years. Why not 20 per cent? Why not 50 per cent? Why not 100 per cent? And so we did a number of special surveys and studies, with intelligence tests as one measure, and we took a particular sort of generation \endash  I can\rquote 
t remember it all n
ow, it was a very complex set of researches. So you take a whole generation, and you find out what has happened to them. You then do various ways of measuring intelligence, which, of course, is controversial, but we tried to be as firm as we could. And we
 studied people\rquote s careers, and why quite a lot of people went downwards in their careers. We tackled it from many many different angles, including some special surveys in which we did measure people\rquote s - youngsters \endash 
 intelligence, and found that X per cent w
ere above a certain level, and only one per cent went into higher education. I mean, in one sense it was straightforward. That means in the sense that it was obvious that limiting university entrance to five per cent of the young population was a class ma
tter, not an intelligence matter \endash  that people didn\rquote t get to university because they couldn\rquote t afford it, or because it didn\rquote t occur to their families, etc.. So it it didn\rquote 
t leave much discussion that it was much too low. The problem was, when one looks back now, how we struggled to justify \endash  and that was a whole central chapter of the Report \endash 
 justify 15 per cent, not overnight, but in ten years. I mean, quite modest in today\rquote s view. Some people on the Committee wanted to go higher, some people thought it wa
s outrageous to go that high. So obviously, at the end there was a judgement, and Lord Robbins had to judge how to pitch the outcome. And he wrote a separate book, a Penguin, on how he justified, on basis of our different research approaches, including so
m
e special surveys of what happens to the young. And, of course, he felt it needed justifying, and, of course, the title of that book became a sort of classic in social research. The pool of ability, so what we were trying to get at, what is society missin
g
? And, of course, we researchers were quite biased, Left-wing and so on, and we were very key. But we were very careful. It was never criticised. There were people who thought that for society to spend that money was a mistake, but as far as I can remembe
r, it was never criticised methodologically. People - social scientists, in particular, felt that we had justified that there was a pool which was not being used... }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
