\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Well, wait a minute. Well, that\rquote s true, in a way, because I was involved before, but in general terms \endash 
 answering your question first - in general terms, this is not a country that has ever been all that comfortable with statistics. Much more now than then, but not as naturally comfortable as Germany and some other countries \endash 
 Canada. But, I mean, it\rquote s sort of accidental, that, in a way. But because the British are a shockingly innumerate society \endash  this is a subject I\rquote m back in, I was at a Board Meeting yes
terday, on the new Company on institutions to do with numeracy, and when I wrote the report on \'93Numeracy and Literacy\'94 for Tony Blair, even I was shocked. We did all the necessary research, and on numeracy \endash 
 and this is strictly relevant to your question \endash 
 on numeracy, in Europe we were the lowest, apart from Poland, and that links to maths teaching at schools, it links to attitudes to mathematics, and it links to a curious snobbishness, and I can summarise it, as I\rquote 
ve often done publicly, in one anecdote. When I was at Rothschild\rquote s, I brought in to meet the Chairman, Evelyn Rothschild, the then head of Burma Oil \endash  that doesn\rquote t exist any more \endash 
 a very big oil company, as you know, and the Head, I don\rquote t remember his name, the top businessman, and during the lunch, I brought him in, hoping that he\rquote d become a client of Rothschild\rquote s \endash  he\rquote s a friend of mine 
\endash  and in the conversation, for some reason, at some point, I referred to compound interest, and the Chairman of Burma Oil said, \'93Oh dear! I have difficulties even with simple interest\'94. Now, what I\rquote 
ve never forgotten is that he was boasting! }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
