\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 This is a source of pride. I\rquote m sure he spoke Latin and Greek fluently! This has always been. It\rquote 
s gradually changing, with the emphasis on mat
hs teaching at schools, and literacy has got a bit better. But when we did The Moser Report on Literacy and Numeracy 11 years, 12 years ago, for Tony Blair - well, for really more credit to the blind Education Minister. Blunkett. When we did that, and we 
did all the necessary research, we found that between 30 and 40 per cent of adults, ordinary adults walking the streets, couldn\rquote t do simple interest, certainly couldn\rquote t measure the size of this carpet \endash 
 20x10, whatever. Many of them couldn\rquote t handle checkout change. So it is a shocker. And so with that goes a sort of feeling that statistics a bit of a joke. I mean, in all the years when I was in top jobs, the hundreds of dinners and lunches I
\rquote ve been at, whenever I\rquote ve said to my neighbours, \'93I\rquote m a statistician\'94, most of the time a bit of a giggle. I mean, it\rquote s not serious. And so it is a serious problem, and that\rquote 
s why it was a wonderful job to do. So I think it is true that it\rquote s not a subject that goes well in this country \endash  certainly not in the past. Also, because people are poor at maths, and don\rquote t worry too much about accuracy \endash 
 numerical accuracy \endash  that led Churchill, no other, led Churchill to set up a CSO in 1940. Churchill said, one day, \'93I can\rquote t stand getting different figures on shipping, and getting 
different figures from there, that Department, that Department, I\rquote m going to have a Central Statistical Office\'94. That\rquote s how it started, and that made an impact, but it\rquote 
s always been a bit of a problem. I think, over the years, and I certainly hope that in my years and my immediate successor\rquote 
s years attitudes improved a bit. It was always slightly easier to get people interested in economic measurements, but stuff like crime or education or health, and that was my field, and that\rquote s what I started at my first
 boss, Harold Wilson, told me to focus. He appointed me because I was a social statistician \endash  that was my interest \endash 
 and he gave me total support, and we did improve all those figures, and we improved public attitudes. I had a wonderful time, and things did change, and went on changing after I\rquote d left \endash  my successor \endash 
 until Mrs. Thatcher came in, and Mrs. Thatcher - I\rquote d already had some battles with her before when she was Education Minister, she wanted to abolish the Census. \'93Who cares about a census?\'94 She didn\rquote 
t think there was such a thing as society. But she was defeated. And so we\rquote d had our rows. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 How do you think she was defeated on that? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
