\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Oh, the rest of the Cabinet. She was only Education. At that point. No, no, she was out-voted. But s
he did make a big impact on - a negative impact - on public statistics, whereas my whole theme, and my successor, John Boreham, our theme was that good figures are necessary for the whole of society, whether you\rquote 
re in a Trade Union, or in a government Department, or in a business, or in a university, or in a school, or just in a family, it\rquote 
s important to have good figures. Now, that was so alien to Mrs. Thatcher, and she did manage to abolish a lot of the figures and a lot of the posts. She accepted that Ministers deserved good statistics, but only Ministers \endash 
 to do their job. So she did do a lot of damage, but some of it was recouped later. And I was very lucky in my three bosses, they were all very keen \endash  Harold Wilson, Ted Heath, and Callaghan \endash  all very 
supportive in improving statistics. But it is a fight, and partly it\rquote s a fight because of what I\rquote ve said about attitude to numbers, innumeracy and all that, and partly the general public doesn\rquote 
t care too much whether politicians are well-informed. So it doesn\rquote t come naturally, and we\rquote 
re now in the middle of another downturn. I mean, this government, in its two years, has done more damage to statistics than Mrs. Thatcher ever managed. As I think I said before, they\rquote ve abolished most of the senior posts, so there\rquote 
s one top post, and most of the other Departmental Heads, Statistical Heads, are no longer what we used to call \'93Under Secretaries\'94, and now, if one\rquote s lucky, what used to be called \'93Assistant Secretary\'94 - it\rquote 
s one level down, and that affects the qual
ity, of course. And numbers are down. So as I mentioned the other day, the excellent Head of the new Statistics Authority, which is a sort of answering body, has not managed to see the Prime Minister once in his four years, although he\rquote 
s highly respected. And constantly has to fight Ministers who say, \'93We\rquote re abolishing everything except figures that Ministers need\'94. So we\rquote re, at the moment, on the way to becoming one of the worst statistical systems \endash 
 we were one of the best. Now, I have great faith in the new Head of the Statistics Authority \endash  Andrew Gillnot. He\rquote s quite tough, and I hope he\rquote 
ll win some of the battles. But it is rather pathetic. I mean, compared to a country like Canada, which is probably the best statistical nation, but France very good, Ge
rmany very good, Belgium, we were near the top in coverage and certainly quality, so that saddens me. But it has to be tackled in the long-term via numeracy. We have to become a country that actually enjoys figures more than it does. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
