\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Well, certainly some hundreds, but part of it was the so-called Office of Populations, Censuses and Surveys, which did the Ce
nsus and other surveys, and social surveys, and that had a big staff. But the biggest controversy \endash 
 this is irrelevant to your question - the biggest controversy throughout my years, before my years, and even now, is between a centralised system and the de
centralised system. Almost every country in the world has a Statistical Office which covers everything. Everything. And we grew up, historically, having a little Statistical Unit in the Ministry of Industry, in the Ministry of Education, etc., etc., and t
hat\rquote s what made Churchill mad, because he got different figures. So he said, \'93We\rquote ve got to have a Central Office\'94
. So then when we had a Central Statistical Office, which took over the economic statistics, but all the other Departments retained, and still retain, their Statistical Units, so we have a strictly decentralised system, almost alone in the world \endash 
 not quite, one or two countries \endash  and we spend countless days and hours and weeks, in my time and since - \'93Shall we change this? Should we go for one single office?\'94
 Now, I was always against that, and I won the reason for being against it was because it was rather marvellous to have a top statistician in the Department of Education, who had daily contact with the Minister. So the argument was, \'93Our stati
sticians are much closer to policy than in these other countries where there\rquote s this abstract office\'94, so to speak. And that one always won the day. And the CSO is really the Treasury\rquote 
s statistics office, so the Treasury has its own office really, and each Department has its office. However, it was Harold Wilson who said, \'93We\rquote 
re going to keep it that way, and you are going to be called Director of the Central Statistics Office and Head of the Government Statistical Service\'94. So I had a double title, and I was kept in charge, and responsible \endash 
 and that meant something \endash  for the whole system. But I kept it decentralised. And it\rquote s been like that, then Mrs. Thatcher managed to get rid of some of the Departmental statisticians, etc., etc., and it\rquote s changed through
 the years. Now, again, that Minister, for example \endash  local government chap, very fat [Eric Pickles] \endash  he is known to be trying to abolish all the statisticians. He wants to get rid of all the statisticians. He said, \'93We don\rquote 
t need them. Don\rquote t need them . We know enough\'94. And he\rquote 
s fighting. And now the overall Authority, the so-called Statistic Authority, which I did help to set up, which Andrew Gilnott will now run, has to fight him. But all those years, we kept our decentralised system because it kept the 
statisticians close to policy, made them much more influential, and that was good news. I think, now, if this kind of government remains, and if I had a voice \endash  which I don\rquote t \endash 
 I would now argue for a single office, because that always says much more single power, and Canada would be the model. That would probably have to come under the Prime Minister, as it does in Canada. So the numbers as a whole - I haven\rquote 
t answered your question. In those days, the Central Statistical Office probably a couple of hundre
d people, but then the rest of the system had many more hundreds, so one ended up with thousands, but, of course, most of them not very senior. And the other thing that\rquote s happened is that the Statistical Office \endash  Central \endash 
 has been moved to Newport, and most of the senior people wouldn\rquote t go, so that\rquote s had a bad effect on quality, and they\rquote ve made many mistakes in recent years. And that\rquote s bad news for statistics. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
