\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Actual mistakes, yeah. I\rquote m talking about not just revising estimates, that\rquote 
s always acceptable because estimates are estimates, but the sort of final National Account figures, last year they got - I\rquote ve got this slightly unfinished in my own mind. There\rquote s one bit of indu
stry, the National Accounts, as you know, are made up of thousands of figures, and they can be quite influential if they go wrong, and they got some wrong. All the figures are based on surveys or particular sources, and it\rquote 
s a jig-saw made up of, literally, thousands and thousands of figures. It\rquote 
s a brilliant invention. But last year, on two occasions, they got two of the industry figures wrong. They made arithmetical mistakes in the office! I mean, actual statisticians making mistakes. It\rquote s possible, but shouldn\rquote t happen \endash 
 not with public figures. I can\rquote t now remember which the two industries were, but on two occasions the result was that the overall estimate of GNP had to be revised. So, of course, that\rquote s really not acceptable. Well, one very senior person
 who was responsible for one of the industry [figures] and oversaw this mistake, was then sacked. I mean, these are sackable mistakes, and so that, of course, is something the Ministers all know, and makes them even more impatient. Yeah. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 You talked
 to Jennifer quite a lot about the problem of Ministers wanting to change the figures for their own purposes. How did you defend yourself against that? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Oh when a Minister - I would probably get to know of it through the Senior Statistician, tried 
to - not necessarily totally give a wrong figure, but at the wrong time, or too late or too early, or not enough detail, or sometimes wrong, and I got to know of it. Maybe the Senior Statisticians came to me, as the boss, and said, \'93
My Secretary of State is trying to delay,\'94 or more often \'93not publish.\'94 That happened quite often. \'93We don\rquote t need to publish this stuff\'94
, if they were embarrassed or something. Now, if I knew that it should be published, or correctly published, etc., I would first of all try to 
ensure that this top statistician was trying to fight that corner, but if the top statistician in the Department of Education said, \'93Well, I\rquote m sorry, my Minister doesn\rquote t want to know\'94
, then I would go and see the Minister of State who, quite often, had the responsibility for statistics in that Department. If I failed to persuade him, I would go and see the Secretary of State, and then I was in the lucky position \endash 
 which they aren\rquote t now \endash  I was able to say to him, \'93Look, this is wrong. You have to publish that figure\'94, or \'93you have to give it in more detail\'94, or whatever I felt was right, and if he still said, \'93I\rquote m sorry, I can
\rquote t agree with you\'94, then I would say, \'93Well, I\rquote ll mention it to the Prime Minister next week\'94, and then they usually gave in. That is 
why the power of being directly under the Prime Minister was so wonderfully crucial - in my time - because they didn\rquote 
t want to have fights with the Prime Minster, over statistics, on the whole. So that nearly always worked, even with a Chancellor. If the Chancellor said \endash  which is more common \endash  that, \'93Here are these economic figures, but they\rquote 
re not really relevant now\'94, I would see the Chancellor quite often, and if he wasn\rquote t playing the game according to my rules, I would simply say, \'93I\rquote ll mention it to the Prime Minister\'94
, which was often enough to make him change his mind. But if not, then the Prime Minister had to intervene, and I certainly recall one day, when I was summoned to Chequers to see Heath, because he was having difficulty with his Labour Min
ister over the unemployment statistics, and he needed my help. So that was the sort of fun of the job! And the only thing that doesn\rquote 
t fit that story is when the Prime Minister, himself, tried to fiddle something, and that happened famously in 1970. I don\rquote t think I\rquote ve already told you this. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 It is rather a crucial story of my time, when I was summoned by Wilson. He was worried that \endash  it\rquote s all in this biography 
\endash  he was worried that the import of new jumbo jets early in 1970 would turn our balance of payments into the negative, and he summoned me, and he explained this. He said, \'93Look, that\rquote s \'a330m.\'94, he said, \'93It\rquote 
s not realistic to include all that in one month, just before the Election. Should we spread it over the year?\'94 I said, \'93Prime Minister, I have just spent six months at the United Nations, a review of the whole world\rquote 
s statistics, and we confirmed one of the rules that imports and exports are measured in the month in which they occur\'94. That was the rule. I said, \'93Prime Minister, that\rquote s the rule\'94. He said, \'93Yes, but this is so unusual\'94
. So he argued. And I said, \'93Well, I\rquote m sorry, these figures are going to come out in January, and it\rquote s quite likely that it\rquote ll turn our balance of payments into the red\'94
. And he went on fighting me for several weeks. I was summoned once or twice, and he telephoned, and sent me notes, and tried everything, including getting his Chancellor, who was a close friend of mine \endash  Roy Jenkins \endash 
 he actually got me out of a performance of Figaro at Glyndebourne, to try to persuade me, and I said, \'93I\rquote m sorry, Chancellor, there\rquote s no way\'94
. I had to stand my ground. I mean, I had my whole staff behind me, and rules are rules, and that\rquote s exactly 
the sort of fiddle that gives statistics a bad name. So I stood my ground, and in the end, I wrote a resignation letter, which I sent. The resignation was not accepted, and he withdrew his pressure. And so the figures were included \endash  the \'a330m. 
\endash  and he did lose the Election, and he never doubted, for a moment, that it was due to that. He was probably wrong, but you will see that in his book. So it\rquote s a very clear story. It\rquote 
s the only one that was quite as extreme. I had one other big row with Dick Crossman, who was Social Services, which covered the Census for some reason. Enoch Powell had just made his \'93rivers of blood\'94
 speech, and of course, his language and attitude was intolerable, but the figures were right \endash  there was this sudden increase in immigration \endash 
 and Dick Crossman tried to stop me publishing it. And I resigned then, but he gave in. So those are the extremes. But really, one has no choice, and one doesn\rquote t want to have a choice. It\rquote 
s not relevant exactly to that, but I did have a wonderful innovat
ion, which was partly my doing. I got the Callaghan government, so it must have been Callaghan who set up a Statistics Policy Committee. It was unique, and never been repeated, unfortunately. And that was a Committee chaired by Edmund Dell, who was a Cabi
net Minister \endash  Labour Cabinet Minister \endash 
 he chaired it, and it had on it three or four Ministers, and several Permanent Secretaries, and the top statisticians, and the issues of statistical policy came to that, and he reported to the Prime Minister. And tha
t was a very helpful bit of machinery, and went on for a little while, but not for terribly long. Mrs. Thatcher didn\rquote t want that sort of thing. And, of course, more statistics high up the agenda, and that\rquote 
s the last thing the present government would want. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Did you have \endash  this is a different question \endash 
 there were other large-scale surveys like the longitudinal studies, and the Household Panel Study and so on, which is more recent, I\rquote m wondering whether you had active contact with those? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Quit
e a lot with the longitudinal surveys. I thought those a wonderful innovation. And I was slightly involved, but very knowledgeable, of the very first longitudinal survey ever done by James Douglas at LSE in the 1940s. Very very early. He invented it reall
y. And then later on there were several others, and they are now the most important source of survey data. No, that\rquote s a wonderful development. I\rquote 
ve never been responsible for one, but the last few times that they were set up, I was always consulted on the sampling and the methodology in general. And, I mean, for many years, I was on the Board of the National Survey Centre, or whatever it\rquote 
s called, with Roger Jowell. I was on the Board, and so I was very involved in all the surveys of that time, including the General Household Survey \endash 
 but I was on the other side of that. I was part of the organisation that did the work for the government. A lot of that is disappearing because }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid8613685 
the government has stopped them}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 . I don\rquote 
t think any of the longitudinal surveys have been cut, but they are terrific, and definitely the future. As I say, I can\rquote t claim any responsibility for them, except for helping them be set up and deciding on the methodology. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Then you\rquote ve also had this \endash  which you\rquote ve just mentioned, actually \endash 
 international role, which I think goes back to the fifties doesn\rquote t it, were you not Secretary of the International Statistical Institute? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Yes. Well, I not only became a member of the ISI, which was top in the national body \endash 
 still exists, always will exist. I think I\rquote d just been President of the Royal Statistical Society. No, perhaps it became before that. Anyway, I got a job, very low level but quite important, secretary. I was the Secretary of the ISI,
 so I got to know - and I went to all the conferences all over the world. I mean, people, in those years, people always regarded my life as a travel club! Statisticians never stop meeting. There\rquote s hardly anywhere in the world I haven\rquote t been 
\endash  usually for a statistical meeting \endash 
 and the ISI meetings spread all over the world, and really, I was very lucky. But my only role for the ISI really, after those early years in which I was Secretary of the Institute, and that was a wonderful introduction. After that I
 became a member, and that was an honour. And then I read papers all the time at conferences, nearly always on social statistics, on survey methods, on sampling, and then, of course, once I\rquote d become head of the statistical system here \endash 
 well, I was that before, actually, yes, I can\rquote t get the timing quite right \endash  then, of course, I would also speak quite a lot at the endless conferences on organisational issues. Because I suppose if I\rquote 
m not going to be over-modest, in some of those years I was the top intern
ational statistician really. I was the most senior head of the statistical system, and the British statistical system was developing wonderfully and very highly regarded, and so those were years in which I was a sort of top dog, and enjoyed it for while i
t lasted. And it was a natural development for somebody who was Head of the CSO. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Did you get new ideas from people in other countries? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Probably more \endash  that\rquote s a good question! Probably, yes, in terms of organisational issues. I mean, once you\rquote 
re in charge of a whole statistical system, and I was - I was also Chairman of the United Nations Statistical Commission for two years, so for two years I was in charge of the whole world\rquote s statistics, so once you\rquote 
re in that sort of role, well, if you\rquote re
 me, you stop having any ideas to do with sampling or methodology. I mean, I was an Organisation man, and I was looked to, endlessly, by others for advice, and that was not just individuals. I spent three months advising the Italian government - at their 
Prime Minister\rquote s request \endash  on improving their statistics. That was a joke, in the sense that when I had my first meeting with the top statistician in Italy, he said, \'93Don\rquote t waste too much time, because we\rquote 
re not really interested\'94. And he said, \'93We always have 50 per cent of our population not covered by statistics, and it\rquote s going to remain like that\'94, he said, \'93but do enjoy yourself\'94
. But anyway, I did that, and I advised some other countries too, and I became a sort of international - it\rquote s difficult to rem
ember it all now, but those were very exciting years, because I was highly regarded, and I was on every conceivable international committee. I spent a lot of time in Geneva. I also spent a year on academic leave of absence in the fifties, working as a sta
tistician for the International Labour Office in Geneva \endash  a whole year. So I did do a lot of international statistical work, apart from speaking at conferences. I was looking \endash  after our last talk \endash 
 I was looking at a list I made after the Robbins Report, a
nd the first year after Robbins I gave 60 public lectures around England, on the Robbins on the statistical side of the Robbins Report. So I had a wonderful time really, and they were wonderful years. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Did you make special friends in other countries? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
