\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
Yes. I became very close to the Canadian top statistician, a guy called Fennecky. He was probably the sort of closest. The others, mean, all Christian name terms, probably almost every country in the world. I\rquote m glad you mentioned the internation
al side because I did spend a lot of each year, in those key years when I was the Head of GSS here, in other countries, and at conferences, which was not just because of me, but people working with me, and politicians, the image of statistics, of official
 
statistics, which is my life, grew and improved. As I ended by saying last time, the public image of official statistics is really what matters to me, and I regard all my methodological academic side earlier, when I was a professor, as a preparation, real
ly, for the years - which is the rest of my life. When I was really in a position, and I hope I used it well, to improve the public standing of good figures on our quality of life. That\rquote 
s what matters to me, and still does, and it really does sadden me that this stupid government is reversing a great deal of that, but hopefully it\rquote 
ll be reversed again. I think it does actually matter that a nation is well-informed about itself. Roger Jowell who was, I suppose, my closest friend \endash  died, very sadly, last Decem
ber, and two weeks ago I spoke and played at his Memorial Service. I was very close to Roger. He was a wonderful man. He was a survey man helped by me, but developed surveys all over Europe, and was Deputy Director of the Authority, under Sir Michael Scho
eder, and was probably the first social scientist who was knighted for all that survey work. I was knighted earlier for when I\rquote d been Head of Statistics. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Can I just ask you one final question, then? I can see you\rquote re looking at your watch! You obviou
sly do have this lifelong interest in statistics and its social relevance, but you did say to Jennifer that your main interest was in the arts. Would you still maintain that? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 It\rquote s really - I mean, one\rquote s allowed to have more than one main interest! I\rquote 
ve never earned money through the arts. My passion in life, since I was a kid, is music, and I love playing, and I love listening. I think I have to claim two equal interests. I think it\rquote 
s fair enough, because music - the peak of my musical life was being Chairman of the Royal Opera House, and, of course, occasionally playing in concerts, but I\rquote 
ve never claimed to be of the standard of a top pianist, nothing like, but good enough to play in amateur concerts and so on. But to be Head of the Royal Opera House, I can\rquote t think of anything more wonderful for a music lover. So that\rquote 
s that side. But what earned me my money, but really I suppose if I had to choose between them, I would have to choose statistics. Funnily enough, it\rquote s even my statistical career that
 led to some of the arts things. I mean, the / thing that changed my life totally was having done statistics as a student, having been an academic for my job. A telephone call from Lionel Robbins \endash  and I remember it to this day \endash 
 a telephone call, asking me to join him in doing the Robbins Report, changed my life. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 Why? }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
\par 
\par Claus:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
(a) Because doing the Robbins Report really led to my other professional jobs. It also led to my being the Head of an Oxford College and so on, and all that. Lionel Robbins m
ade me a Fellow of the Academy that led to all that. Lionel Robbins put me on the Board of the Royal Opera House, so I think of that step, which was sort of academic \endash 
 joining the Robbins Committee - but if you put your final question in a slightly different way, which is if you were to say to me, \'93What am I proudest of in my life?\'94
 it would be my ten years, or however many years, Head of Statistics, because all right, maybe I was a good Chairman of the Royal Opera House, I don\rquote t know, but I certainly enjoyed it! And lots of other things I\rquote 
ve done I hope I did reasonably well. Head of a College, okay. But where I actually changed a bit of the world, and like everybody else, I feel that one should try to leave this world having made a little change somewhere,
 and so, for me, that would be my years as Head of the CSO, definitely, because that\rquote 
s when I could actually try to change the way a nation looks at itself. And what makes the final years, now, sad, is that that can all disappear because of one lousy government, but perhaps not for always. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid5510798\charrsid5510798 
